82.- Quae yravis Aesopum] Claudius Aesopus, the tragic actor, was an intimate friend of Cicero’s, and most of the distin- guished men of that time. He was older than Cicero, though the date of his birth is not known, or that of his death. He was a freedman of some person ,belonging to the Clodia gens. Speaking of enunciation Quintilian applies the same epithet to Aesopus that Horace does: ‘¹ Plus autem affectus habeant lentiora: ideoque Roscius citatior, Aesopus gravior fuit, quod ille comoedias hic tragoedias egit ” (xi. 3. lll). Cicero makes Quintus compare Aesopus' delivery with his own, and speaks of him as showing ‘¹ tantum ardorem vultuum atque motuum ut eum vis quaedam abstraxisse a sensu mentis videretur '¹ (de Div. i. 37). ⁴ Gravis ' is a good epithet for a tragic actor.

— quae doctus Roscius emh] Q. Ros- cius, the comic actor, was also an intimate friend of Cicero, who often speaks of him, and pleaded a cause for him in a speech still in part extant. Cicero speaks of ‘⁴ Roscii gestus et venustas¹' (de Orat. l. 59). and illustrates the description of Quintilian given above, “Roscius citatior,” by saying (de Legg. i. 4) that when he was getting old “numeros in cantu cecidit ipsasque tardiores fecit tibias.'' His enunciation was rapid when he was young, but he was obliged to slacken it in his old age. The meaning of ‘ doctus ' can only be explained of the study he gave to his profession, and

the accurate knowledge he acquired of the principles of his art. He died about Ass-c. 692, and was enormously rich, like Aesopus, whose wealth has been referred to on S. ii.
